Forties Crude Remains at Seven-Week High; Shell Offers Urals

-- B y   S h e r r y   S u
-- 
2011-03-17T17:27:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-17/forties-crude-remains-at-seven-week-high-shell-offers-urals.html
  North Sea  Forties crude remained at
a seven-week high after BP Plc failed to buy a cargo for the
second day. Russian Urals fell after Royal Dutch Shell Plc
sought to sell Urals in northwest Europe without success.  North Sea  BP lowered its bid for 600,000 barrels of Forties for
loading April 2 to April 4 by 10 cents to a premium of 10 cents
to benchmark Dated Brent, according to a survey of traders and
brokers monitoring the daily Platts trading window.  Chevron Corp. was unable to buy a cargo for April 5 to
April 9 at parity to Dated Brent, while Vitol Group didn’t
manage to buy a shipment for April 6 to April 9 at 10 cents
above Dated Brent, the survey showed.  Shell offered a consignment of Forties for April 2 to April
4 at 20 cents more than Dated Brent without attracting any
buyers, according to the survey.  Shell also failed to sell a cargo of Russian Urals for
March 27 to March 31 delivery to Rotterdam at $3.60 below Dated
Brent, compared with a discount of $3.55 it made yesterday, the
survey showed. Glencore International AG sought to buy a
shipment for the same loading date at $3.95 below Dated Brent
without success.  Urals in northwest  Europe  was assessed at $3.58 below Dated
Brent today, down 8 cents from yesterday, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  Reported North Sea market activity typically occurs during
the Platts window that ends at 4:30 p.m. in  London . Prior to the
window, Forties loading 10 to 21 days in the future cost 22
cents more than Dated Brent, unchanged from yesterday, Bloomberg
data showed.  Brent for May settlement traded at $114.01 a barrel on the
London-based ICE Futures Europe exchange at the close of the
window, up from $110.90 yesterday. The June contract was at
$113.83, 18 cents less expensive than May.  Mediterranean  No bids or offers for Urals were made in the Mediterranean.
Yesterday Eni SpA failed to buy 80,000 tons for loading March 29
to April 2 at $2.90 a barrel below Dated Brent.  Urals rose by 43 cents to a discount of $2.85 to Dated
Brent in the Mediterranean today, according to Bloomberg data.  West Africa  Exports of  Chad ’s Doba and  Equatorial Guinea ’s Ceiba crudes
will be unchanged at four cargoes each in May, according to
loading programs obtained by Bloomberg News.  To contact the reporter on this story:
